Cell["\t", "TechNoteText",
 TabFilling->"\[LongDash]\[NegativeThickSpace]",
 TabSpacings->Scaled[1],
 FontColor->GrayLevel[0.85],
 CellID->1050865502,ExpressionUUID->"8e2d38de-9b99-42f1-86c5-5a817a25c885"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "In the above, we have examined the possibility to realize an arbitrary \
rotation ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["U", TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "59a3b1ed-1c69-4192-a03f-78891cfe3b46"],
 " to a desired accuracy ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["\[Epsilon]", TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "27174282-347e-45e1-9334-c95c26a2def0"],
 ". There remains an important question: how many discrete rotations should \
you take to achieve the target accuracy? Intuitively, one may argue that \
roughly ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"\[ScriptCapitalO]", "(", 
    RowBox[{"1", "/", "\[Epsilon]"}], ")"}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "67ee4d45-b8b8-4fa9-a5e2-67a6c57157f2"],
 " gates are required. Surprisingly, the ",
 StyleBox["Solovay-Kitaev theorem",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " states that the convergence rate is much faster and that the number of \
required discrete rotations is only ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"\[ScriptCapitalO]", "(", 
    RowBox[{
     SuperscriptBox["log", "\[Gamma]"], "(", 
     RowBox[{"1", "/", "\[Epsilon]"}], ")"}], ")"}], TraditionalForm]],
  ExpressionUUID->"c3e65fe7-13e5-4e55-86c0-23f44018124b"],
 " with ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"\[Gamma]", " ", "\[TildeTilde]", " ", "2.2"}], TraditionalForm]],
  ExpressionUUID->"cb819ea4-6834-49ee-9b7a-544218e6989c"],
 "."
}], "TechNoteText",
 CellID->2020243574,ExpressionUUID->"3d43d8ee-1250-4a2b-ae37-0de287fe3c12"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The difference becomes even more significant when we consider a quantum \
circuit composed of ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["N", TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "33bc556d-7380-49c2-b634-cd2ad7ecb54f"],
 " gates with each involving a single-qubit rotation. Suppose that we want to \
implement the quantum circuit to an overall accuracy ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["\[Epsilon]", TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "d48c18ee-b3b8-4cb8-89ec-1c670afc1a46"],
 ". Then, each gate must be implemented to the accuracy ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"\[Epsilon]", "/", "N"}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "076dd02a-4765-49a1-9e59-0b3034f19a90"],
 ". The above intuitive estimation would suggest that we need ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"\[ScriptCapitalO]", "(", 
     RowBox[{"N", "\[Times]", 
      RowBox[{"1", "/", 
       RowBox[{"(", 
        RowBox[{"\[Epsilon]", "/", "N"}], ")"}]}]}], ")"}], "=", 
    RowBox[{"\[ScriptCapitalO]", "(", 
     RowBox[{
      SuperscriptBox["N", "2"], "/", "\[Epsilon]"}], ")"}]}], 
   TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->"6afe0f72-be61-4518-a712-0f82323df071"],
 " gates. However, according to the Solovay-Kitaev theorem, ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"\[ScriptCapitalO]", "(", 
    RowBox[{"N", " ", 
     RowBox[{
      SuperscriptBox["log", "\[Gamma]"], "(", 
      RowBox[{"1", "/", "\[Epsilon]"}], ")"}]}], ")"}], TraditionalForm]],
  ExpressionUUID->"2abddfc8-6dc4-4797-a06b-87d1239d0f55"],
 " gates is sufficient to achieve the same accuracy. While the cost increases \
quadratically in ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["N", TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "650e9cd2-9894-4494-bdf6-236e7dea766f"],
 " in the former estimation, it does only poly-logarithmic in the latter."
}], "TechNoteText",
 CellID->1753630972,ExpressionUUID->"b2419e07-3929-4163-9273-727a58a5da17"]
}, Open  ]],

